i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":49,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Westbrome was born in 1500, in Gilberdyke, Yorkshire, England, his father, Thomas Westbrome 13th ggf, was 20 and his mother, Dorothy Hillary, was 20. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Robert Westbrome. He died about 1550, in Fingringhoe, Essex, England, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1500–about 1550":"1500–umbes 1550","1500–1550":"1500–1550","1502–Female":"1502–Surnud","1526–1594":"1526–1594","1480–Male":"1480–Surnud","1480–Female":"1480–Surnud","1502":"1502","1500":"1500","1499":"1499","about 1526":"umbes 1526","1594":"1594","1550":"1550","about 1550":"umbes 1550","1480":"1480","1549":"1549","1526":"1526","Gilberdyke, Yorkshire, England":"Gilberdyke, Yorkshire, England","Gilberdike, East Yorkshire, 